The main problem is that X.500 is analogous to a 20 foot cube of fine
marble.  Its proponents claim that it is made out of magnificent
material, has great potential, and contains a work of art superior to
Michelangelo's David.  Its critics see only a cube, sometimes in the
middle of the road.

In less abstract terms, while the specification and prototype
implementations you mention do have impressive features and capabilities
for data types, etc., you also have a "user-friendly" names that are not
user-friendly to type, at least one prototype implementation that does
not implement multiple name servers, and a distributed database
specification which does not use its own services to keep track of
redundant copies and/or database distribution information.  Of course,
other implementations are already better, and missing features can be
added.

paul

